{"title_page": "CervicalCheck cancer scandal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n\nThe '''[[CervicalCheck]] cancer scandal''' first emerged in 2018 and involved several women in the [[Republic of Ireland]] suing the [[Health Service Executive]] (HSE) after they received incorrect [[smear test]] results for [[cervical cancer]].<ref name=\"mother of two3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/mother-of-two-sues-hse-for-alleged-cervical-cancer-diagnosis-delay-838223.html|title=Mother-of-two sues HSE for alleged cervical cancer diagnosis delay|date=19 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/cervical-check-3980626-Apr2018/|title=CervicalCheck chief responds to test criticism: 'I\u2019d be surprised if women didn't have questions'|last=Aodha|first=Gr\u00e1inne N\u00ed|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514065056/http://www.thejournal.ie/cervical-check-3980626-Apr2018/|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live|access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/i-m-dying-because-of-human-error-and-that-s-disgusting-1.3490935|title=\u2018I\u2019m dying because of human error and that's disgusting\u2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514141459/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/i-m-dying-because-of-human-error-and-that-s-disgusting-1.3490935|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live|access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[Vicky Phelan]], a mother of two children from Annacrotty, Co. Limerick, underwent a smear test for cervical cancer. Although her test showed no abnormalities, she was diagnosed with cervical cancer in 2014. An internal CervicalCheck review found the original result to be incorrect, but Phelan was not informed of this fact until 2017. She sued Clinical Pathology Laboratories Inc, Austin, Texas, over the incorrect test. The case was settled for \u20ac2.5 million without admission of liability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/courts/high-court/woman-with-terminal-cancer-gets-2-5m-high-court-settlement-1.3473814|title=Woman with terminal cancer gets \u20ac2.5m High Court settlement|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref> 14 other women in the 2014 review were also found to have 'false-negative' test results.\n\nOn 26 April 2018 the HSE confirmed that 206 women had developed cervical cancer after having a misdiagnosed CervicalCheck smear test.<ref name=\"women2063\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/smear-test-scandal-206-women-develop-cancer-after-allclear-36850237.html|title=Smear test scandal: 206 women develop cancer after all-clear|date=27 April 2018|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=2018-05-12}}</ref> Of these, 162 had not been told that the initial results were incorrect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/it-isn-t-a-helpline-it-s-an-answering-machine-women-hit-out-at-hse-cancer-phone-service-1.3480235|title=\u2018It isn\u2019t a helpline, it\u2019s an answering machine\u2019 - women hit out at HSE cancer phone service|last=Power|first=Jack|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> Dr Grainne Flannelly, CervicalCheck's clinical director, stepped down on 28 April. A week earlier it was reported that Dr Flannelly had in 2017 advised a gynaecologist not to advise women about the re-evaluated test results, but to file the results instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/cancer-controversy-director-of-cervicalcheck-stands-down-1.3477975|title=Cancer controversy: director of CervicalCheck stands down|last=Towey|first=Niamh|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the controversy, the Irish Department of Health announced on 8 May 2018 that a scoping inquiry was being established, to be carried out by Dr Gabriel Scally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.gov.ie/blog/press-release/scoping-inquiry-established-into-the-cervicalcheck-screening-programme-and-dr-gabriel-scally-appointed-to-lead-it/|title=Scoping Inquiry established into the CervicalCheck Screening Programme and Dr Gabriel Scally appointed to lead it {{!}} Department of Health|website=health.gov.ie|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nIn May, HSE director-general Tony O'Brien took temporary leave of absence from the board of a US medical company amid renewed calls for him to stand aside from his position due to the ongoing controversy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/hse-chief-tony-o-brien-to-take-leave-of-absence-from-us-board-1.3482685|title=HSE chief Tony O\u2019Brien to take leave of absence from US board|date=3 May 2015|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=2018-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505205135/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/hse-chief-tony-o-brien-to-take-leave-of-absence-from-us-board-1.3482685|archive-date=2018-05-05|url-status=live}}</ref> Tony O'Brien announced his resignation as director-general of the HSE with effect from close of business on 11 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/hse-boss-tony-obrien-steps-down-in-wake-of-cervicalcheck-scandal-36894958.html|title=HSE boss Tony O\u2019Brien steps down in wake of CervicalCheck scandal|date=10 May 2018|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 September 2018 the Department of Health published Dr Scally's final report.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scally|first=Gabriel|last2=Health (DoH)|first2=Department of|date=2018-09-12|title=Scoping Inquiry into the CervicalCheck Screening Programme: final report|url=https://www.lenus.ie/handle/10147/623840|language=en}}</ref> The report gathered testimony from women and families affected by the scandal, and conducted an investigation and audit of the CervicalCheck programme. It also contained 50 recommendations covering access to medical records, governance of CervicalCheck, procurement of laboratory services and revision of the HSE's open disclosure policy.\n\nEmma Mhic Mhath\u00fana, a terminally ill mother of five children who was one of the women given an inaccurate negative test made national media headlines in May, including an interview on [[Morning Ireland]].<ref name=\"Emma13\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/the-doctor-told-me-the-smear-results-i-got-in-2013-were-wrong-1.3480441|title=The doctor told me the smear results I got in 2013 were wrong|last=Power|first=Jack|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=2018-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502005713/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/the-doctor-told-me-the-smear-results-i-got-in-2013-were-wrong-1.3480441|archive-date=2018-05-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Emma23\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/emma-mhic-mhath%C3%BAna-calls-for-hse-to-be-dismantled-1.3492397|title=Emma Mhic Mhath\u00fana calls for HSE to be dismantled|last=Gleeson|first=Colin|date=11 May 2018|accessdate=2018-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512113025/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/emma-mhic-mhath%C3%BAna-calls-for-hse-to-be-dismantled-1.3492397|archive-date=2018-05-12|url-status=live}}</ref> Appearing on ''[[The Late Late Show (Irish TV series)|The Late Late Show]]'', she called for the HSE to be \"dismantled and reassembled\". Mhic Mhath\u00fana passed away on 7 October 2018.\n\nVicky Phelan, a terminally ill mother of two children, whose legal case against the state was one of the catalysts for the publication of the controversy, was named as one of [[the BBC]]'s [[100 Women (BBC)#2018|100 Women]] in 2018.<ref name=\"mother of two3\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-46225038|title=100 Women 2018: What to look forward to|date=19 November 2018|access-date=2018-11-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120065219/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-46225038|archive-date=2018-11-20|url-status=live|work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n\nIncreased scrutiny into BreastCheck and BowelScreen has followed from this controversy.<ref name=\"BreastCheck claims3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/state-claims-agency-dealing-with-four-alleged-misdiagnosis-cases-involving-breastcheck-tds-told-36894048.html|title=State Claims Agency dealing with four alleged misdiagnosis cases involving BreastCheck, TDs told|last=McQuinn|first=Cormac|date=10 May 2018|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=2018-05-12}}</ref><ref name=\"Bowel Scrutiny3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/breast-and-bowel-tests-now-under-scrutiny-as-public-fear-screening-36864836.html|title=Breast and bowel tests now under scrutiny as public fear screening|last=O'Regan|first=Eilish|date=2 May 2018|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 December 2018, Minister for Health Simon Harris TD published an implementation plan based on Dr Scally's report.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Health (DoH)|first=Department of|date=2018-12-11|title=Implementation Plan for Report of the Scoping Inquiry into CervicalCheck Issues|url=https://www.lenus.ie/handle/10147/623996|language=en}}</ref> The plan set out 126 actions arising from the report's recommendations. Announcing an independent review of the plan, Minister Harris said:<blockquote>I welcome [Dr Sally's] initial assessment of this Plan and his confirmation that he is satisfied that all parties are taking seriously his findings and recommendations, that resources have been allocated to take the work forward at a high level of priority, and that the proposed work programme is impressive in its commitment to making rapid progress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.gov.ie/blog/press-release/minister-harris-publishes-the-implementation-plan-for-the-recommendations-of-dr-gabriel-scally-on-the-cervicalcheck-screening-programme/|title=Minister Harris publishes the Implementation Plan for the recommendations of Dr Gabriel Scally on the CervicalCheck Screening Programme {{!}} Department of Health|website=health.gov.ie|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n<references group=\"\"></references><blockquote></blockquote>\n\n[[Category:2018 in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Cancer screening]]\n[[Category:Medical scandals in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the Republic of Ireland]]\n\n{{Ireland-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n\nThe '''2018 [[CervicalCheck]] cancer scandal''' involved several women in the [[Republic of Ireland]] suing the [[Health Service Executive]] (HSE) for receiving incorrect [[smear test]] results for [[cervical cancer]].<ref name=\"mother of two3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/mother-of-two-sues-hse-for-alleged-cervical-cancer-diagnosis-delay-838223.html|title=Mother-of-two sues HSE for alleged cervical cancer diagnosis delay|date=19 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/cervical-check-3980626-Apr2018/|title=CervicalCheck chief responds to test criticism: 'I\u2019d be surprised if women didn't have questions'|last=Aodha|first=Gr\u00e1inne N\u00ed|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514065056/http://www.thejournal.ie/cervical-check-3980626-Apr2018/|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live|access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/i-m-dying-because-of-human-error-and-that-s-disgusting-1.3490935|title=\u2018I\u2019m dying because of human error and that's disgusting\u2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514141459/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/i-m-dying-because-of-human-error-and-that-s-disgusting-1.3490935|archive-date=2018-05-14|url-status=live|access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, [[Vicky Phelan]], a mother of two children from Annacrotty, Co. Limerick, underwent a smear test for cervical cancer. Although her test showed no abnormalities, she was diagnosed with cervical cancer in 2014. An internal CervicalCheck review found the original result to be incorrect, but Phelan was not informed of this fact until 2017. She sued Clinical Pathology Laboratories Inc, Austin, Texas, over the incorrect test. The case was settled for \u20ac2.5 million without admission of liability.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/courts/high-court/woman-with-terminal-cancer-gets-2-5m-high-court-settlement-1.3473814|title=Woman with terminal cancer gets \u20ac2.5m High Court settlement|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref> 14 other women in the 2014 review were also found to have 'false-negative' test results.\n\nOn 26 April 2018 the HSE confirmed that 206 women had developed cervical cancer after having a misdiagnosed CervicalCheck smear test.<ref name=\"women2063\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/smear-test-scandal-206-women-develop-cancer-after-allclear-36850237.html|title=Smear test scandal: 206 women develop cancer after all-clear|date=27 April 2018|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=2018-05-12}}</ref> Of these, 162 had not been told that the initial results were incorrect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/it-isn-t-a-helpline-it-s-an-answering-machine-women-hit-out-at-hse-cancer-phone-service-1.3480235|title=\u2018It isn\u2019t a helpline, it\u2019s an answering machine\u2019 - women hit out at HSE cancer phone service|last=Power|first=Jack|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-01-14}}</ref> Dr Grainne Flannelly, CervicalCheck's clinical director, stepped down on 28 April. A week earlier it was reported that Dr Flannelly had in 2017 advised a gynaecologist not to advise women about the re-evaluated test results, but to file the results instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/cancer-controversy-director-of-cervicalcheck-stands-down-1.3477975|title=Cancer controversy: director of CervicalCheck stands down|last=Towey|first=Niamh|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the controversy, the Irish Department of Health announced on 8 May 2018 that a scoping inquiry was being established, to be carried out by Dr Gabriel Scally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.gov.ie/blog/press-release/scoping-inquiry-established-into-the-cervicalcheck-screening-programme-and-dr-gabriel-scally-appointed-to-lead-it/|title=Scoping Inquiry established into the CervicalCheck Screening Programme and Dr Gabriel Scally appointed to lead it {{!}} Department of Health|website=health.gov.ie|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref>\n\nIn May, HSE director-general Tony O'Brien took temporary leave of absence from the board of a US medical company amid renewed calls for him to stand aside from his position due to the ongoing controversy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/hse-chief-tony-o-brien-to-take-leave-of-absence-from-us-board-1.3482685|title=HSE chief Tony O\u2019Brien to take leave of absence from US board|date=3 May 2015|work=[[The Irish Times]]|accessdate=2018-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180505205135/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/hse-chief-tony-o-brien-to-take-leave-of-absence-from-us-board-1.3482685|archive-date=2018-05-05|url-status=live}}</ref> Tony O'Brien announced his resignation as director-general of the HSE with effect from close of business on 11 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/hse-boss-tony-obrien-steps-down-in-wake-of-cervicalcheck-scandal-36894958.html|title=HSE boss Tony O\u2019Brien steps down in wake of CervicalCheck scandal|date=10 May 2018|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 September 2018 the Department of Health published Dr Scally's final report.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scally|first=Gabriel|last2=Health (DoH)|first2=Department of|date=2018-09-12|title=Scoping Inquiry into the CervicalCheck Screening Programme: final report|url=https://www.lenus.ie/handle/10147/623840|language=en}}</ref> The report gathered testimony from women and families affected by the scandal, and conducted an investigation and audit of the CervicalCheck programme. It also contained 50 recommendations covering access to medical records, governance of CervicalCheck, procurement of laboratory services and revision of the HSE's open disclosure policy.\n\nEmma Mhic Mhath\u00fana, a terminally ill mother of five children who was one of the women given an inaccurate negative test made national media headlines in May, including an interview on [[Morning Ireland]].<ref name=\"Emma13\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/the-doctor-told-me-the-smear-results-i-got-in-2013-were-wrong-1.3480441|title=The doctor told me the smear results I got in 2013 were wrong|last=Power|first=Jack|date=1 May 2018|accessdate=2018-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502005713/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/the-doctor-told-me-the-smear-results-i-got-in-2013-were-wrong-1.3480441|archive-date=2018-05-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Emma23\">{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/emma-mhic-mhath%C3%BAna-calls-for-hse-to-be-dismantled-1.3492397|title=Emma Mhic Mhath\u00fana calls for HSE to be dismantled|last=Gleeson|first=Colin|date=11 May 2018|accessdate=2018-05-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512113025/https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/emma-mhic-mhath%C3%BAna-calls-for-hse-to-be-dismantled-1.3492397|archive-date=2018-05-12|url-status=live}}</ref> Appearing on ''[[The Late Late Show (Irish TV series)|The Late Late Show]]'', she called for the HSE to be \"dismantled and reassembled\". Mhic Mhath\u00fana passed away on 7 October 2018.\n\nVicky Phelan, a terminally ill mother of two children, whose legal case against the state was one of the catalysts for the publication of the controversy, was named as one of [[the BBC]]'s [[100 Women (BBC)#2018|100 Women]] in 2018.<ref name=\"mother of two3\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-46225038|title=100 Women 2018: What to look forward to|date=19 November 2018|access-date=2018-11-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120065219/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-46225038|archive-date=2018-11-20|url-status=live|work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n\nIncreased scrutiny into BreastCheck and BowelScreen has followed from this controversy.<ref name=\"BreastCheck claims3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/state-claims-agency-dealing-with-four-alleged-misdiagnosis-cases-involving-breastcheck-tds-told-36894048.html|title=State Claims Agency dealing with four alleged misdiagnosis cases involving BreastCheck, TDs told|last=McQuinn|first=Cormac|date=10 May 2018|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=2018-05-12}}</ref><ref name=\"Bowel Scrutiny3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/health/breast-and-bowel-tests-now-under-scrutiny-as-public-fear-screening-36864836.html|title=Breast and bowel tests now under scrutiny as public fear screening|last=O'Regan|first=Eilish|date=2 May 2018|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=2018-05-12}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 December 2018, Minister for Health Simon Harris TD published an implementation plan based on Dr Scally's report.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Health (DoH)|first=Department of|date=2018-12-11|title=Implementation Plan for Report of the Scoping Inquiry into CervicalCheck Issues|url=https://www.lenus.ie/handle/10147/623996|language=en}}</ref> The plan set out 126 actions arising from the report's recommendations. Announcing an independent review of the plan, Minister Harris said:<blockquote>I welcome [Dr Sally's] initial assessment of this Plan and his confirmation that he is satisfied that all parties are taking seriously his findings and recommendations, that resources have been allocated to take the work forward at a high level of priority, and that the proposed work programme is impressive in its commitment to making rapid progress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://health.gov.ie/blog/press-release/minister-harris-publishes-the-implementation-plan-for-the-recommendations-of-dr-gabriel-scally-on-the-cervicalcheck-screening-programme/|title=Minister Harris publishes the Implementation Plan for the recommendations of Dr Gabriel Scally on the CervicalCheck Screening Programme {{!}} Department of Health|website=health.gov.ie|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n<references group=\"\"></references><blockquote></blockquote>\n\n[[Category:2018 in the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Cancer screening]]\n[[Category:Medical scandals in Ireland]]\n[[Category:Political scandals in the Republic of Ireland]]\n\n{{Ireland-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bygmester", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CervicalCheck_cancer_scandal"}
{"title_page": "Charles Stone III", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American film director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charles Stone III\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1966}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| occupation = Film director\n}}\n\n'''Charles Stone III''' (born 1966) is an American film director. He is best known for ''[[Drumline (film)|Drumline]]'' starring [[Nick Cannon]], ''[[Mr. 3000]]'' starring [[Bernie Mac]], and ''[[Paid in Full (2002 film)|Paid in Full]]''.\n\nStone directed the video to \"[[Illadelph Halflife|What They Do]]\" by [[The Roots]], featuring the group running through many rap video clich\u00e9s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2pt1f_the-roots-what-they-do_music |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206162051/http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2pt1f_the-roots-what-they-do_music |archivedate=December 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nStone is the creator of the popular [[advertising campaign]] \"[[Whassup?]]\" for [[Budweiser]] in 1999.  In October 2008, he directed a spoof of this campaign to depict his critical view of the Republican Party's eight years in the White House and to support the presidential campaign of [[Barack Obama]].\n\nA 1984 graduate of [[Central High School (Philadelphia)|Central High School]] in [[Philadelphia]], he is the son of Louise Davis Stone and journalist and [[Tuskegee Airman]] [[Chuck Stone]].\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n* ''[[Drumline (film)|Drumline]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Paid in Full (2002 film)|Paid in Full]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Mr. 3000]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[CrazySexyCool: The TLC Story]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Just Keke]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Lila & Eve]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Step Sisters]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Uncle Drew]]'' (2018)\n\n===Television===\n* ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Lincoln Heights (TV series)|Lincoln Heights]]'' (2007\u201309)\n* ''Spaced'' (2008) (TV movie)\n* ''[[CrazySexyCool: The TLC Story]]'' (2013) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Greenleaf (TV series)|Greenleaf]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Black-ish]]'' (2018\u201319)\n* ''[[Black Monday (TV series)|Black Monday]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Bigger (TV series)|Bigger]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Mixed-ish]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Zoey's Extraordinary Playlist]]'' (2020)\n\n==Music videos directed by Charles Stone III==\n<ref>{{cite web|last=Ducker|first=Eric|title=On The Job Training: Part Five|url=http://www.waxpoetics.com/features/articles/on-the-job-training-part-five|publisher=waxpoetics.com|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Charles Stone III |url=http://www.mvdbase.com/tech.php?last=Stone+III&first=Charles|work=director videography|publisher=mvd.com|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref> \n* [[Living Colour]] \u2013 \"[[Funny Vibe (song)|Funny Vibe]]\"\n* Living Colour \u2013 \"[[Elvis Is Dead]]\"\n* [[Colin James]] \u2013 \"[[Just Came Back]]\"\n* [[A Tribe Called Quest]] \u2013 \"[[I Left My Wallet in El Segundo]]\"\n* A Tribe Called Quest \u2013 \"[[Bonita Applebum]]\"\n* [[Tragedy Khadafi|Intelligent Hoodlum]] \u2013 \"Arrest the President\"\n* [[Public Enemy (band)|Public Enemy]] \u2013 \"[[911 Is a Joke]]\"\n* [[Black Sheep (group)|Black Sheep]] \u2013 \"[[The Choice Is Yours (Revisited)]]\"\n* [[Boogie Down Productions|Harmony]] \u2013 \"Poundcake\"\n* [[Fu-Schnickens]] \u2013 \"[[La Schmoove]]\"\n* Fu-Schnickens \u2013 \"[[True Fuschnick|True Fu-Schnick]]\"\n* [[After 7]] \u2013 \"Can He Love U Like This\"\n* [[Neneh Cherry]] featuring [[Guru (rapper)|Guru]] \u2013 \"Sassy\"\n* [[The Roots]] \u2013 \"Distortion to Static\"\n* [[Eric Ben\u00e9t]] \u2013 \"Let's Stay Together\"\n* [[Screaming Headless Torsos]] \u2013 \"Vinnie\"\n* [[Vernon Reid]] \u2013 \"Mistaken Identity\"\n* The Roots \u2013 \"Concerto of the Desparado\"\n* The Roots \u2013 \"What They Do\"\n* [[Large Professor]] \u2013 \"[[I Juswannachill|Ijustwannachill]]\"\n* [[Artifacts (group)|Artifacts]] \u2013 \"The Ultimate\"\n* [[Stephen Simmonds]] \u2013 \"Get Down\"\n* [[Ultra Nat\u00e9]] \u2013 \"[[Found a Cure (Ultra Nat\u00e9 song)|Found a Cure]]\"\n* [[P.M. Dawn]] featuring [[John Fort\u00e9]] & [[Ky-Mani Marley]] \u2013 \"Gotta Be...Movin On Up\"\n* P.M. Dawn \u2013 \"I Had No Right\"\n* The Roots featuring [[Erykah Badu]] \u2013 \"[[You Got Me (The Roots song)|You Got Me]]\"\n* The Roots \u2013 \"[[The Next Movement]]\"\n* [[Shootyz Groove]] \u2013 \"L Train\"\n* [[Quad City DJ's]] \u2013 \"Let's Do It\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{imdb name|id=0831690|name=Charles Stone III}}\n\n{{Charles Stone III}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stone, Charles, III}}\n[[Category:1966 births|Stone, Charles, III]]\n[[Category:African-American film directors]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:Central High School (Philadelphia) alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n\n{{US-film-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|American film director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Charles Stone III\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1966}}\n| birth_place = [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| occupation = Film director\n}}\n\n'''Charles Stone III''' (born 1966) is an American film director. He is best known for ''[[Drumline (film)|Drumline]]'' starring [[Nick Cannon]], ''[[Mr. 3000]]'' starring [[Bernie Mac]], and ''[[Paid in Full (2002 film)|Paid in Full]]''.\n\nStone directed the video to \"[[Illadelph Halflife|What They Do]]\" by [[The Roots]], featuring the group running through many rap video clich\u00e9s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2pt1f_the-roots-what-they-do_music |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206162051/http://www.dailymotion.com/video/x2pt1f_the-roots-what-they-do_music |archivedate=December 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nStone is the creator of the popular [[advertising campaign]] \"[[Whassup?]]\" for [[Budweiser]] in 1999.  In October 2008, he directed a spoof of this campaign to depict his critical view of the Republican Party's eight years in the White House and to support the presidential campaign of [[Barack Obama]].\n\nA 1984 graduate of [[Central High School (Philadelphia)|Central High School]] in [[Philadelphia]], he is the son of Louise Davis Stone and journalist and [[Tuskegee Airman]] [[Chuck Stone]].\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n* ''[[Drumline (film)|Drumline]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Paid in Full (2002 film)|Paid in Full]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Mr. 3000]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[CrazySexyCool: The TLC Story]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Just Keke]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Lila & Eve]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Step Sisters]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Uncle Drew]]'' (2018)\n\n===Television===\n* ''[[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Lincoln Heights (TV series)|Lincoln Heights]]'' (2007\u201309)\n* ''Spaced'' (2008) (TV movie)\n* ''[[CrazySexyCool: The TLC Story]]'' (2013) (TV movie)\n* ''[[Greenleaf (TV series)|Greenleaf]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Black-ish]]'' (2018\u201319)\n* ''[[Black Monday (TV series)|Black Monday]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Bigger (TV series)|Bigger]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Mixed-ish]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Zoey's Extraordinary Playlist]]'' (2020) - episode #9: \"[[Zoey's Extraordinary Playlist#ep9|Zoey's Extraordinary Silence]]\"\n\n==Music videos directed by Charles Stone III==\n<ref>{{cite web|last=Ducker|first=Eric|title=On The Job Training: Part Five|url=http://www.waxpoetics.com/features/articles/on-the-job-training-part-five|publisher=waxpoetics.com|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Charles Stone III |url=http://www.mvdbase.com/tech.php?last=Stone+III&first=Charles|work=director videography|publisher=mvd.com|accessdate=December 9, 2012}}</r