{"title_page": "Cardinham Grange", "text_new": "'''Cardinham Grange''' was a [[Monastic grange|monastic grange]] in [[Cardinham]], [[Cornwall]], UK. Lady Vale Chapel was given soon after the Norman Conquest by Richard Fitz Turold to the Abbey of St Mary de Valle near [[Bayeux]] intending that a cell of monks should be established. The abbey, finding the property burdensome, induced Richard to transfer it to the monastery of [[Tywardreath]] which he was then founding. It was served by monks from Tywardreath until the dissolution of the monasteries when the property was granted to the [[Duchy of Cornwall]].<ref>''Cornish Church Guide'' (1925) Truro: Blackford; p. 72</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|50.471477|-4.651401|type:landmark_region:GB_source:Wikimapia_scale:2000|name=Cardinham Grange (poss.)|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Monasteries in Cornwall]]\n\n{{Cornwall-struct-stub}}\n{{UK-Christian-monastery-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Cardinham Grange''' was a grange in [[Cardinham]], [[Cornwall]], UK. Lady Vale Chapel was given soon after the Norman Conquest by Richard Fitz Turold to the Abbey of St Mary de Valle near [[Bayeux]] intending that a cell of monks should be established. The abbey, finding the property burdensome, induced Richard to transfer it to the monastery of [[Tywardreath]] which he was then founding. It was served by monks from Tywardreath until the dissolution of the monasteries when the property was granted to the [[Duchy of Cornwall]].<ref>''Cornish Church Guide'' (1925) Truro: Blackford; p. 72</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord|50.471477|-4.651401|type:landmark_region:GB_source:Wikimapia_scale:2000|name=Cardinham Grange (poss.)|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Monasteries in Cornwall]]\n\n{{Cornwall-struct-stub}}\n{{UK-Christian-monastery-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Verne Equinox", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardinham_Grange"}
{"title_page": "Kenny McLean", "text_new": "{{for|the musician|Kenny MacLean}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name           = Kenny McLean\n|image          = \n|image_size     = \n|caption        = \n|fullname       = Kenneth McLean<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1335777 |title=2019/20 Premier League squads confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=3 September 2019 |accessdate=3 September 2019}}</ref>\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1992|1|8|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Rutherglen]], Scotland\n|height         = {{convert|1.83|m|order=flip}}<ref name=sbase/>\n|position       = [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|Central midfielder]] / [[Midfielder#Winger|Left midfielder]]\n|currentclub    = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n|clubnumber     = 23\n|youthyears1    =\n|youthclubs1    = [[Aberdeen F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Aberdeen]]\n|youthyears2    = 2006\u20132008\n|youthclubs2    = [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]]\n|youthyears3    = 2008\u20132009\n|youthclubs3    = [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]\n|years1         = 2009\u20132015\n|clubs1         = [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]\n|caps1          = 131\n|goals1         = 20\n|years2         = 2009\u20132010\n|clubs2         = \u2192 [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]] (loan)\n|caps2          = 20\n|goals2         = 1\n|years3         = 2015\u20132018\n|clubs3         = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]\n|caps3          = 111\n|goals3         = 13\n|years4         = 2018\u2013\n|clubs4         = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]\n|caps4          = 47\n|goals4         = 4\n|years5         = 2018\n|clubs5         = \u2192 [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] (loan)\n|caps5          = 15\n|goals5         = 5\n|nationalyears1 = 2010\n|nationalteam1  = [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland U19]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 1\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 2011\u20132014\n|nationalteam2  = [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]]\n|nationalcaps2  = 11\n|nationalgoals2 = 0\n|nationalyears3 = 2016\u2013\n|nationalteam3  = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n|nationalcaps3  = 10\n|nationalgoals3 = 1\n|club-update    = 09:23, 8 March 2020 (UTC)\n|ntupdate       = 07:54, 14 October 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Kenneth McLean''' (born 8 January 1992) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] or [[Midfielder#Winger|left midfielder]] for {{English football updater|NorwichC}} club [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]. He is known for being a massive Billy Gilmour fan and often praises the protestant pirlo for inspiring him to become a footballer, he has posters of the Gilmour all over his room and house. McLean is also a massive Ipswich fan. \n\nAfter being released by  [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers' youth team]], McLean started his senior career at SPL club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]. He went on loan to [[Scottish Second Division|Second Division]] side [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]] for the second half of the [[2009\u201310 Scottish First Division|2009\u201310 season]], before returning to St Mirren and breaking into the first team. He moved to [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] in 2015. In January 2018, he joined [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] but was loaned back to Aberdeen until the end of the season.\n\nHe represented Scotland at the [[Scotland national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[Scotland Under-21 national football team|under-21]] international levels before making his debut for the [[Scotland national football team|senior Scotland team]] in 2016.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early life and career===\nMcLean was born in [[Rutherglen]] and attended [[Cathkin High School]] in [[Cambuslang]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/duncan-weir-happy-to-be-glasgow-s-flag-bearer-1-3320000 |title=Duncan Weir happy to be Glasgow's flag-bearer |first=David |last=Ferguson |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=26 February 2014 |accessdate=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cathkin\">{{cite news| url =  http://www.rutherglenreformer.co.uk/rutherglen-sport/local-rutherglen-sport/2011/11/02/football-shining-performance-from-cambuslang-lad-in-spl-63227-29701737/ | title =  Football: Shining performance from Cambuslang lad in SPL  | publisher = |work=  Rutherglen Reformer | date =   2 November 2011 | accessdate = 10 November 2011}}</ref> He spent time with the youth setups of both [[Aberdeen F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Aberdeen]] and [[Rangers F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Rangers]] as a schoolboy.<ref name=maddad>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/st-mirren-kid-kenny-mclean-1084460|title=St Mirren kid Kenny McLean jokes Rangers-mad dad could kick him out for helping Buddies draw at Ibrox|date=17 October 2011|accessdate=1 December 2017|newspaper=Daily Record}}</ref><ref name=returns>{{cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/555999/Kenny-McLean-Aberdeen-return|title=Kenny McLean returns to club he walked out on|date=3 February 2015|accessdate=1 December 2017|newspaper=Daily Express}}</ref> In 2008, he decided not to renew his Rangers contract and joined [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=853 |title=Through the Ranks: Kenny McLean |publisher=St Mirren F.C. |date=15 February 2011 |accessdate=16 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405191717/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=853 |archivedate= 5 April 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Arbroath (loan)===\nMcLean moved on loan from St Mirren to [[Scottish Second Division|Second Division]] club [[Arbroath F.C.|Arbroath]] in December 2009. Arbroath signed McLean, along with [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] striker [[Daniel McKay]], to cover for injuries.<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arbroath/8409639.stm | title =  SPL youth duo join Red Lichties | website = BBC Sport | date =   12 December 2011 | accessdate = 2 December 2011}}</ref> On 12 December, McLean made his debut for Arbroath in a 4\u20133 loss to [[Stirling Albion F.C.|Stirling Albion]]. Shortly after this match, Arbroath signed McLean's St Mirren teammate [[Kyle Faulds]] on loan.<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/a/arbroath/8422496.stm | title =  Buddies' Faulds joins Arbroath  | website = BBC Sport | date =   19 December 2009 | accessdate = 2 December 2011}}</ref> On 10 April, McLean scored his only goal for Arbroath, a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] in a 4\u20132 loss against Stirling Albion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/football/second/results/3151655/ |title=Arbroath 2 \u2013 4 Stirling Albion : Saturday |publisher=Scottish Football League |date=10 April 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110106110238/http://www.scottishfootballleague.com/football/second/results/3151655/ |archivedate= 6 January 2011 }}</ref> He made a total of 23 appearances during the second half of the [[2009\u201310 Scottish Second Division|2009\u201310 season]].<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/spl/prized_asset_mclean_lifted_by_levein_s_tv_name_check_1_1955061 | title =  Prized asset McLean lifted by Levein's TV name check\n | publisher = Johnston Press | work = The Scotsman | date =   11 November 2011 | accessdate = 11 November 2011}}</ref> Arbroath were relegated to the [[Scottish Third Division|Third Division]] at the end of the season, after losing to [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Athletic]] in the [[2009-10 Scottish Second Division#Final|relegation play-off]].<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/st-mirren/willing-conscript-mclean-ready-for-national-service-1.1133813 | title =  Willing conscript McLean ready for national service | publisher =  Herald & Times Group | work = The Herald | date =   9 November 2011 | accessdate = 11 November 2011}}</ref> McLean has said that his loan spell at Arbroath helped him develop as a player and also to become more mature.<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/2011/11/09/st-mirren-ace-kenny-mclean-loan-spell-at-arbroath-has-helped-me-take-spl-by-storm-86908-23548702/ | title =  St Mirren ace Kenny McLean: Loan spell at Arbroath has helped me take SPL by storm  | publisher = Trinity Mirror | work = Daily Record | date =   9 November 2011 | accessdate = 3 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===St Mirren===\nEighteen-year-old McLean made his debut on 17 October 2010, coming on as a substitute in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton]]. St Mirren were 2\u20130 down when he came on and their manager, [[Danny Lennon]], thought that they were going to lose anyway so he would bring a youngster on. However, ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' noted that McLean's \"drive and energy\" lifted St Mirren and helped them to turn the game around and get a draw.<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/hamilton-academicals/st-mirren-2-hamilton-2-teenage-kicks-hush-undertones-1.1062013 | title =  St Mirren 2 Hamilton 2: Teenage kicks hush undertones | publisher =  Herald & Times Group  | work = The Herald | date =   17 October 2011 | accessdate = 11 November 2011}}</ref> Three days after his debut, McLean made his first start for St Mirren, in a 3\u20130 loss to [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]].<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/st_mirren/9135760.stm | title =  Kenny McLean delight at St Mirren extension  | website = BBC Sport | date =   28 October 2011 | accessdate = 19 November 2011}}</ref> Later in the week he signed a three-year contract extension, tying him to the club until 2014.<ref name=\"Cathkin\" /> He then made his first home start, in a 1\u20130 loss to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] on 16 November. After this match he thanked his manager for having faith in him and also said that he was amazed by the fact that only six months before he was playing in the [[2009-10 Scottish Second Division#Final|Second Division relegation play-off]], but was now playing against some of the best players in the country.<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/saints-teenager-kenny-homing-in-on-start-slot-1.1068809 | title =  Saints teenager Kenny homing in on start slot | publisher = Herald & Times Group | work = Evening Times | date =   16 November 2010 | accessdate = 19 November 2011}}</ref> He went on to make a total of 23 appearances during the [[2010\u201311 St Mirren F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]].<ref>{{Soccerbase season|52534|2010|name=Kenny McLean|accessdate=2 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n''[[Sky Sports]]'' said that during the [[2011\u201312 St Mirren F.C. season|2011\u201312 season]] McLean had begun to emerge as one of the top young talents in the SPL.<ref name=\"DifferentBeans\" /> His first game of the season was on 6 August, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]], where he came on as an 80th-minute substitute.<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14351959.stm | title = St Mirren 1\u20131 Dundee United | website = BBC Sport | date =   6 August 2011 | accessdate = 19 November 2011}}</ref> His first start came a week later in a 1\u20130 loss to [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]].<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14429730.stm | title =  St Mirren 0\u20131 Motherwell | website = BBC Sport | date =   13 August 2011 | accessdate = 19 November 2011}}</ref> McLean then played regularly in the first team over the next few months and was in excellent form.<ref>{{Soccerbase season|52534|2011|name=Kenny McLean|accessdate=19 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://www.paisleydailyexpress.co.uk/renfrewshire-sport/renfrewshire-football/renfrewshire-football-st-mirren/2011/10/31/lennon-hails-king-kenny-87085-29687682/ | title =  Lennon hails 'King' Kenny  | publisher = | work = Paisley Daily Express | date =   31 October 2011 | accessdate = 10 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=7565 |title=Kenny McLean \u2013 Young Player of the Month |publisher=St Mirren F.C. |date=8 November 2011 |accessdate=13 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120405191647/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=7565 |archivedate= 5 April 2012 }}</ref> He scored his first senior goal in a 1\u20130 win over [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] on 29 October<ref>{{cite news   | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15413558.stm | title =  St Johnstone 0\u20131 St Mirren | website = BBC Sport | date =   29 October 2011 | accessdate = 10 November 2011}}</ref> and was rewarded with the SPL Young Player of the Month award for October 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/15620821.stm|title=SPL young player award for St Mirren's Kenny McLean|accessdate=8 November 2011|date=8 November 2011|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> After this, teammate [[Gary Teale]] said that he thought McLean was very similar to former [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] captain [[Barry Ferguson]], and that he thought McLean would have a brilliant future in the game.<ref name=\"GaryTeale\">{{cite news   | url =  http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/gaz-buddies-kid-kenny-reminds-me-of-young-baz-1.1134205 | title =  Gaz: Buddies kid Kenny reminds me of young Baz | publisher = Herald & Times Group | work = Evening Times  | date =   10 November 2011 | accessdate = 10 November 2011}}</ref> In the weeks leading up to his award, McLean had been watched by [[English Championship]] clubs [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] also reportedly interested in him.<ref name=\"DifferentBeans\">{{cite news   | url =  http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/7307076/McLean-ignoring-speculation | title =  McLean ignoring speculation | publisher = BSkyB | work = Sky Sports | date =   13 November 2011 | accessdate = 19 November 2011}}</ref> Lennon encouraged interest from other clubs, saying that he took it as a compliment to McLean's development. But he also said that he would not consider selling McLean in the near future and expressed his delight at the fact that he had already signed McLean on a long-term contract.<ref name=\"TinofBeans\" /> On 19 November, McLean scored his second goal for St Mirren, in a 2\u20131 win over [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news   | url =  https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5gpWD5qB6REXy7Qj3YwmbRi0VLCzg?docId=N0747521321706126178A | title =  Saints too strong for Pars | publisher = | work = UK Press Association | date =   19 November 2011 | accessdate = 19 November 2011}}</ref> He then scored St Mirren's first goal, on 10 December, as they came from behind to secure a 2\u20132 draw against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].<ref>{{cite news\n | url =  http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/16015650.stm\n | title =  Aberdeen 2 \u2013 2 St Mirren\n | website =   BBC Sport\n | date =   10 December 2011\n | accessdate = 10 December 2011}}</ref> McLean was one of the four players nominated for the SPL young Player of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite news\n | url =  https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5j-ewcnOmUOeEXdnHO3MODohRndxA?docId=N0436561334925517374A\n | title =  Lennon: McLean top class\n | publisher =   The Press Association\n | date =   20 April 2012\n | accessdate = 30 April 2012}}</ref> In January 2014 it was announced that McLean would be out-of-action for 6 weeks following knee surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25612715|title=St Mirren's Kenny McLean to undergo knee surgery|date=5 January 2014|accessdate=5 January 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 July 2014 it was announced that McLean had a signed a two-year contract extension with the club, following much speculation that he would leave the club in the summer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28132100|title=St Mirren: Kenny McLean signs new two year contract|date=2 July 2014|accessdate=2 July 2014|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===Aberdeen===\nMcLean signed a three-and-a-half-year contract with [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] on 2 February 2015, for a reported transfer fee of around \u00a3300,000.<ref name=returns/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/the-dons/dons-sign-kenny-mclean-for-275-000-1.821502 | title=Dons sign Kenny McLean for \u00a3275,000 | publisher=evening express | work=evening express | date=2 February 2015 | accessdate=2 February 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202191442/http://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/the-dons/dons-sign-kenny-mclean-for-275-000-1.821502 | archivedate=2 February 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31094119|title=Kenny McLean completes move from St Mirren to Aberdeen|date=2 February 2015|accessdate=2 February 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> He made his debut for the club the following weekend in a [[Scottish Premiership|league]] game against [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]], which Aberdeen won 4\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31071154|title=Aberdeen 4 \u2013 0 Ross County|date=7 February 2015|accessdate=9 February 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 16 July 2015, McLean scored his first goal for Aberdeen in a 3\u20130 win away to [[HNK Rijeka]] in the second qualifying round first leg of the [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=HNK Rijeka 0\u20133 Aberdeen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/33517070|website=BBC Sport|last=Davie|first=Scott|date=16 July 2015|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> McLean scored his first league goal for Aberdeen in a 1\u20130 win over Dundee United on the opening day of the [[2015\u201316 Scottish Premiership|2015\u201316 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33667198|title=Dundee United 0-1 Aberdeen|date=2 August 2015|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, McLean confirmed that he would not be renewing his Aberdeen contract when it expired the following summer.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/football/i-want-to-leave-aberdeen-on-a-high-says-kenny-mclean/ | title=I want to leave Aberdeen on a high, says Kenny McLean| publisher=evening express | work=evening express | date=10 November 2017 | accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHaving helped the team to finish runners-up in the [[2017\u201318 Scottish Premiership]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44020123|title=Aberdeen win at champions Celtic to secure second place in the Scottish Premiership|website=BBC Sport|date=13 May 2018|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> \u2013 as in each of his other three campaigns with the club \u2013 McLean finally departed Aberdeen after making 158 appearances and scoring 25 goals during his spell at [[Pittodrie Stadium|Pittodrie]] (including the loan back after signing for Norwich).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://backoffice.afc.co.uk/Team/CurrentSquad/player_show.cfm?player_id=7205|title=Kenny McLean|publisher=AFC Heritage Trust|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Norwich City===\nMcLean was sold in January 2018 to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]], who loaned him back to Aberdeen for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web|title=City complete deal for Kenny McLean|url=http://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2018/january/kenny-mclean-signs|publisher=Norwich City FC |date=22 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42769118|title=Aberdeen's Kenny McLean heads for Norwich City|date=21 January 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42778874|title=Kenny McLean: Norwich City sign midfielder and loan him back to Aberdeen|date=22 January 2018|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nHaving missed a portion of his first season in English football with an ankle ligament injury,<ref name=contract19/> in December 2018 he commented that he was determined to prove he was good enough.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sundaypost.com/fp/i-need-to-get-back-playing-as-soon-as-possible-to-prove-to-people-im-good-enough-for-english-football|title=Former Aberdeen star Kenny McLean: \"I need to get back playing as soon as possible to prove I'm good enough for English football\"|first=Mark|last=Guidi|publisher=Sunday Post|date=17 December 2018}}</ref> He returned to the ''Canaries'' team to help the club gain promotion to the [[Premier League]] as winners of the [[2018\u201319 EFL Championship]], with his enthusiastic title celebrations (addressing the crowd of supporters as the 'Mayor of Norwich' with a ceremonial hat and bottle of [[Mogen David|fortified wine]]) receiving media attention.<ref>[https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/kenny-mclean-toasts-norwich-city-15004548 Kenny McLean toasts Norwich City title in classic Glasgow fashion with a bottle of MadDog 2020], Daily Record, 6 May 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/fp/sport/football/english-football/ex-don-mclean-extends-bank-holiday-in-role-of-mayor-after-norwichs-premier-league-promotion/ Ex-Don McLean 'extends' bank holiday in role of 'mayor' after Norwich's Premier League promotion], Evening Express, 7 May 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/17684235.from-md-2020-to-euro-2020-mayor-of-norwich-kenny-mclean-is-now-looking-to-toast-scotland-success/ From MD 20/20 to Euro 2020 - Mayor of Norwich Kenny McLean is now looking to toast Scotland success], The Herald, 5 June 2019</ref> In the 2019 close season, he signed an improved contract.<ref name=contract19>[https://www.canaries.co.uk/News/2019/june/kenny-mclean-signs-new-norwich-city-contract/ Kenny McLean signs new Norwich City contract], Norwich City FC, 17 June 2019</ref>\n\n==International career==\nMcLean earned his first call-up for [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland under-19 squad]] in October 2010, coming on as a 58th-minute substitute in a 4\u20132 win over [[Norway national under-19 football team|Norway]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=823&playerID=42197&squadID=9|title=Scottish Football Association|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, he was called up to the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21 team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/9432663.stm|title=Darren Cole and Kenny McLean given Scots Under-21 call|accessdate=25 March 2011|date=22 March 2011|website=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu21/player.php?playerid=515|title=Scotland U21 profile |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref> Making his debut, again from the bench, as Scotland beat [[Belgium national under-19 football team|Belgium]] 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/football_player_profile.cfm?page=823&playerID=42197&squadID=5|title=Scottish Football Association|publisher=}}</ref> He was not selected for the Scotland under-21 team to play in a [[2013 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship qualification Group 10|2013 European Under-21 Football Championship qualification]] match against the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]] on 14 November 2011.<ref name=\"TinofBeans\"/> [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] manager [[Danny Lennon]] expressed his surprise at McLean being left out of the squad. ''[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]'' said that this was understandable given that he was \"among the on-form midfielders of his age group\" at the time.<ref name=\"TinofBeans\"/>\n\nMcLean received his first call-up to the senior [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad in March 2016, for a friendly against [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35770855|title=Scotland: Six new call-ups for Czech Republic and Denmark friendlies|date=10 March 2016|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref> McLean made his international debut in that game, playing 57 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35898391 |title=Czech Republic 0-1 Scotland: Kenny McLean hungry for more caps |website=BBC Sport |date=25 March 2016 |accessdate=25 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotland/player.php?playerid=1198 |title=Scotland  profile |publisher=Fitbastats.com |accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was called up again in October 2017, for a friendly match against [[Netherlands national football team|the Netherlands]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41796933|title=Scotland: Interim manager Malky Mackay calls up three new faces for friendly|date=30 October 2017|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\nHe scored his first Scotland goal in March 2019 in a 2-0 away win against [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/season=2020/matches/round=2001086/match=2026045/index.html?iv=true|title=European Qualifiers - San Marino-Scotland|first=|last=UEFA.com|website=UEFA.com}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nMcLean's favoured position is as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]], but he can also play as a [[Midfielder#Winger|left midfielder]]. He has said that he favours playing in the centre because he can get more of the ball and influence play more than when he is on the left. He is a naturally attacking player and when playing in the centre he makes runs to and beyond the striker which adds an extra dimension to his team's play.<ref name=\"CentralPerk\">{{cite news | url =  http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/sport/saints-star-s-hopes-for-a-central-perk-1.1132472 | title =  Saints star's hopes for a central perk| publisher =   Glasgow Evening Times | date =   1 November 2011 | accessdate = 10 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] international, and McLean's teammate at [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]], [[Gary Teale]] has compared him to [[Barry Ferguson]]. Teale said that McLean had shown incredible maturity at such a young age and that from their first training session together he could see McLean's talent. McLean has an excellent first touch and is also very composed and assured on the ball. McLean also has very high energy, work rate and athleticism which enable him to make lots of attacking runs.<ref name=\"GaryTeale\" /> McLean's manager at St Mirren, [[Danny Lennon]], said that he thought McLean was an excellent passer and that he could \"open a tin of beans\" with his left foot and was also decent with his right. Lennon also said that McLean was a rare type of Scottish player because he was always looking for a 'slide-rule' pass and he was actually capable of delivering them.<ref name=\"TinofBeans\">{{cite news | url =  http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/st-mirren/manager-encourages-clubs-to-look-at-mclean-1.1134013 | title =  Manager encourages clubs to look at McLean | publisher =   HeraldScotland | date =   10 November 2011| accessdate = 10 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|5 May 2019}}<ref name=sbase>{{soccerbase|52534}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Scottish Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\" valign=\"center\"|[[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]\n|[[2009\u201310 St Mirren F.C. season|2009\